The start symbol is  
S → NT0 NT1  

NT1 can produce only a single terminal and nothing else:
NT1 → 't12' | 't51' | 't67' | 't46' | 't80' | 't73' | 't42'

Therefore any string in the language must end with one of  
t12, t51, t67, t46, t80, t73, t42.

The given string ends with t2, which NT1 can never produce.  
Hence no derivation from the grammar can generate the entire string.

No

The start symbol S expands as

S → NT0 NT1

Because the grammar is in Chomsky normal form, NT0 must generate a contiguous prefix of the string, while NT1 must generate the corresponding contiguous suffix.

NT1, however, has no productions other than single-terminal ones:

NT1 → 't12' | 't51' | 't67' | 't80' | 't73' | 't46' | 't42'

Hence any substring derived from NT1 must be exactly one terminal long and must be one of the seven listed terminals.

The given string ends with the terminal “t50”.  “t50” is not in NT1’s list, so the suffix required by S → NT0 NT1 cannot be produced by NT1.  Consequently the whole string cannot be generated by the grammar.

No
